abstract: Procter & Gamble has appointed activist investor Nelson Peltz to its board following a certified recount of shareholder votes cast at its annual meeting in October.

headline_main: New York Today: Decking the Halls at Gracie Mansion

abstract: While the Trump administration has moved to block one media deal, the president offered support to another — and said that it would be a “great thing” for jobs.
snippet: While the Trump administration has moved to block one media deal, the president offered support to another — and said that it would be a “great thing” for jobs.
lead_paragraph: Good Thursday. Here’s what we’re watching:

lead_paragraph: The political news cycle is fast, and keeping up can be overwhelming. Trying to find differing perspectives worth your time is even harder. That’s why we have scoured the internet for political writing from the right and left that you might not have seen.

abstract: The Central Park Conservancy named Elizabeth Smith, a former assistant parks commissioner, to be its president and chief executive.
snippet: The Central Park Conservancy named Elizabeth Smith, a former assistant parks commissioner, to be its president and chief executive.
lead_paragraph: Elizabeth W. Smith grew up in Rye, N.Y., about an hour north of Manhattan, and said her earliest memory of Central Park was from when she moved to the Upper East Side after college. She would go running around the park — not in the park itself, but on the sidewalks just outside the stone walls that surround it.

abstract: Leaders, businesspeople and investors from around the world gathered near Paris at the invitation of the French president, who warned “we are losing the battle” against climate change.
snippet: Leaders, businesspeople and investors from around the world gathered near Paris at the invitation of the French president, who warned “we are losing the battle” against climate change.
lead_paragraph: BOULOGNE-BILLANCOURT, France — Money was on everybody’s mind at the climate summit meeting organized here on Tuesday, as President Emmanuel Macron of France tried to shore up support for the Paris climate deal by urging heads of state, chief executives and investors to commit more funding to the fight against global warming.

abstract: Mr. Hanley served for four decades in New York City’s labor relations office and won productivity gains and respect from union negotiators.
snippet: Mr. Hanley served for four decades in New York City’s labor relations office and won productivity gains and respect from union negotiators.
lead_paragraph: James F. Hanley, who started work as a union electrician and went on to become New York City’s chief labor negotiator for nearly 15 years, died on Wednesday on Staten Island. He was 69.
